calls.temp$date <- as.Date(calls.temp$date)
calls.temp$dow <- weekdays(calls.temp$date)
calls.temp$day <- day(calls.temp$date)
calls.temp$month <- substr(calls.temp$date, 6, 7)

Subset Data

This was the call type used for this project:

calls.type <- calls.temp %>%
  group_by(type) %>%
  summarise(count = n()) %>%
  mutate(PCT = round(count/sum(count)*100,2))
calls <- subset(calls.temp, calls.temp$type == 'LARCENY')

Basic Statistics

calls.day <- calls %>%
  group_by(date) %>%
  summarise(count = n())

first <- min(calls.day$date)
last <- max(calls.day$date)

calls.day <- calls.day %>% 
  complete(date = seq(ymd(first), 
                      ymd(last), 
                      "day")) %>%
  mutate(dow = wday(date, label = T, week_start = 1), 
         month.name = month(date, label = T, abbr = F),
         month.num = substr(date, 6,7),
         week = isoweek(date),
         day = day(date),
         year = year(date))

calls.day$count[is.na(calls.day$count)] = "0"
calls.day$count <- as.numeric(calls.day$count)

Analysis for Hour of Day

The first temporal graph, which represents calls based on an hour of day and day of week ratio, shows the areas of hot and cold spots for each weekday change throughout the day and remain steady throughout the week. Between the times of 2200-0700 hours, there are a small number of calls; this is our cold spot which accounts for little activity and is represented by white spaces. However, as the day progresses from 0700-1000 hours, the calls increase, which is represented by purple spaces. Between the times of 1100-1700 hours, this gap has the highest calls, this is our hot spot or the strongest area of concentration and is represented by blue spaces. Towards the end of each day, between the hours 1800-2300 hours, the call counts begin to decrease which is again by white spaces. Based on this data, there is a noticeable pattern of hot and cold spots remaining the same throughout the hours of the day and days of week with Friday being the peak day of week for receiving the most call counts between the times of 1300-1600 hours.

Analysis for Day of Week

In the first histogram, which represents day of week ratio with the x-axis being the number of calls per day and the y-axis being the number of days with activity, and the third temporal graph, there is a trend to be recognized. The number of call counts seems to be different based on the day of week causing the hot and cold spots to differentiate. Cold spots occur more frequently at the beginning of the week, specifically on Sundays, while hot spots occur more frequently during the end of the week, specifically Thursdays, Fridays, and Saturdays. Looking at future predictions in the next coming week, we can assume Sunday will have the least number of call counts ranging between 0-25, while Monday-Wednesday will have around 50-75 call counts, and Thursday-Saturday will have around 75-100 call counts.

Analysis for Month of Year

The third temporal graph, which represents a month-of-year ratio, this data shows that hot and cold spots vary across the past 16 years with little patterns, but a noticeable trend. Between the years of 2007-2010, the data shows an increase in call counts with a hot spot occurring in July of 2008-2010, December of 2010-2011, and January of 2023. Looking at cold spots, there is a cold spot in July of 2019; however, between 2011-2020, there is a major decrease in overall call counts accounting for a large cold spot. In 2021, numbers begin to increase and have been continuing to increase each year; this shift might be due to Covid-19 when quarantine occurred from 2020-2021 causing many people to lose jobs and remain at home. However, quarantine ended at the end of 2021; this gave people more freedom and opportunities to commit crimes in 2022 due to the hard loss of jobs. Call activity over the past few months and years has been increasing; looking at future predictions for the next month, August, we can assume next month will have a relatively high count that might have a 45-55 call count range.
